Words cannot sufficiently describe the joy and shock I felt watching those modules actually spin before my eyes. Sure, the offsets were wrong. Sure, the PID control values needed tuning. But nevertheless, we had something to work off of.

From there, it was properly integrating the drivetrain code into our complex architecture, ensuring working odometry so our robot tracked properly during autonomous, incorporating snaps, tuning autos, we were on a roll. 

My role as a subteam lead extends far beyond simply writing code for the robot. Though a 10 person subteam may not sound considerably large, with only one robot to work on, it is quite difficult to ensure that every member is fully involved. This had been a persisting issue with the subteam far before I even joined the team. I remember that as the new member, I spent the vast majority of my freshman year simply pushing around the robot or placing game elements when resetting in between autos. My understanding of the codebase barely extended beyond the few glimpses I caught of a veteran member‚Äôs screen. 

As subteam lead, this was one of the main issues I hoped to attack. I wanted to ensure that every single member of my subteam, both new and veteran, had a chance to write and test code on the robots. No more sitting in a corner watching a select few veteran members struggle with the codebase ‚Äî I wanted everyone to participate as much as they could, I wanted everyone to have the best experience possible.

Thus, I spent a considerable amount of time and energy focused on developing a training curriculum that would sufficiently prepare my new members.

‚ÄúI can‚Äôt back down now.‚Äù Those words spiraled in my head as I forcefully blinked out the fatigue in my eyes. 

The clock read 3:00 AM in the morning, and I was still in the shop. 

It was the night before our first offseason competition of the year, and after 2 whole years of virtual events my robotics team was desperate to compete. And yet, the pandemic had taken a hard toll on the entire team.

As the Software Robot subteam lead of my high school FRC robotics team, Team 1678 Citrus Circuits, I saw first hand how difficult it was to maintain sustainability within the team throughout the pandemic. The huge drop in knowledge seen across all subteams caused confusion and loss that visibility held us back as we entered into the offseason. 

What's more, our desire to try using swerve modules for the offseason instead of our usual tank drivetrain meant we were venturing out into new ground with no previous knowledge from past students to fall back upon. 

Thus, walking into the position, I felt unspeakably lost. With barely a year‚Äôs worth of training and experience, I found little knowledge to help me lift the weight and responsibility I now carried. My once self-confident nature was crushed. The responsibility of completing tasks I felt wholly unprepared for was overwhelming.

But I didn‚Äôt have a choice.

They always say the hardest step to take is the first one, and so I knew I had to get started somehow. I had to find a path for the subteam to follow throughout the offseason to bring us back to the world championship level team we once were.
